      {
        id: 'lambda', fn: 'lambda', desc: 'Create a small anonymous function inline.',
        category: 'Functions', subtitle: 'Single-expression anonymous function for sort keys and callbacks',
        signature: 'lambda args: expression',
        descLong: 'lambda creates an anonymous function limited to a single expression. It is most useful as a sort key, callback, or argument to higher-order functions. For anything more complex — multiple statements, conditionals, loops — use def instead.',
        code: `# Basic:
square = lambda x: x**2
add    = lambda x, y: x + y
square(5)   # 25
add(3, 4)   # 7

# Most common use — sort keys:
people = [("Alice", 30), ("Bob", 25), ("Carol", 35)]
sorted(people, key=lambda p: p[1])              # by age
sorted(people, key=lambda p: (-p[1], p[0]))     # desc age, asc name
# In map/filter (though comprehensions are usually clearer):
list(map(lambda x: x**2, range(5)))
list(filter(lambda x: x > 0, [-1, 2, -3, 4]))
# As callback / argument:
buttons = [Button(text="OK",     callback=lambda: confirm()),
           Button(text="Cancel", callback=lambda: cancel())]
# Closure over loop variable — WRONG:
fns = [lambda: i for i in range(3)]
fns[0]()   # 2, not 0 — all capture same i!
# Fix — default argument captures value at definition time:
fns = [lambda i=i: i for i in range(3)]
fns[0]()   # 0 ✓`,
        tips: [
